Title: Far Cry 5: Official Announce Trailer | Ubisoft [NA]
Comment: Poor game. I'm a big far cry fan, (its probably my favourite game franchise) but far cry 2, 3, 4 and Primal had way better stories. this campaign was short, didn't seem to have much of a story ark, and i wasn't invested at all in the story. not enough secondary objectives. I felt like i really got deep into the worlds that 2,3,4 and primal created, playing them for months each. i crapped this game out in a couple of weeks and now dont really feel like i can go back to it and have much fun. I miss the ability of being able to re-do outposts like in 4. The outposts in 5 didn't really feel like they were outposts, i felt like they weren't labelled well enough on the map, they didn't have enough character, and taking them down wasn't much fun either, it wasn't a challenge, it wasn't rewarding, and all we got each time was some guy waving an american flag or something...cheap. i feel like the only exciting part of the game was the first 20 minutes i spent on the first island after you leave the bunker, that was the only part of the world that was well fleshed out. when it comes to setting- i feel like america was just too familiar to most of us. its a boring setting. you dont feel like you can go wild there, even if it is part of one of the most wild parts of the country. it just isn't as fun as africa or the himalaya or desert islands. very disappointed not to have seen any reference at all to native americans (montana has more indians than anywhere else in the US) and it was one of the few interesting parts of going to america for Europeans like me, native languages and culture are a huge part of how america developed as a country and we just dont see any of it?!?! Though half the population seemed to be black, which i also found very distracting and not realistic at all for montana! Montana population stat breakdown- 89% white, 6.3% native americans [which is huge] and 0.3% black [which is nothing]!!!! i think was a politically driven move and the game has suffered for it. very poor idea from the creators. i worked that out in my head and then had a look at the official stats. game developers had years to sort this out! very dissapointing! Now before you say im racist, i think having different ethnicities in games is a really big step forward that games should strive for, but for goodness sake make it realistic, otherwise it just isn't a believable world, and i cant get immersed in it. All in all, worst Far cry ive played so far, wouldn't recommend buying it to people. All that aside, i am a huge fan and am really looking forward to the next one, in the hope that it smashes it out the park with a big fresh idea!

This way you can safely enter the center without being knocked out. Have fun messing with the guarding Peggies and you have to get a helicopter to get inside the main building. don‚Äôt fast travel or it will reset the invincibility. Inside the building, there‚Äôs a room where one of the scenes take place. Hopefully they don‚Äôt patch this.

Title: Far Cry 5: Official Announce Trailer | Ubisoft [NA]
Comment: The guy who did Bioshock Infinite did this... That game was amazing from a writing standpoint, and it tells you a lot about the direction this game might take.. I just hope they ask good questions here. Jesus has nothing to do with forcing religion through violence. This could actually be a really good thing for Christians if it treats the religion with fairness instead of putting all religious people in one box. Pastor Jerome is one of the heroes which should tell you a lot. If they make him true to the faith - A non-violent character or someone who wouldn't carry a gun - I think that would actually be way more powerful or interesting from a narrative standpoint and a gaming standpoint. So many religious people getting upset about this game- I think it could actually be a really positive thing for Christians if the story is well told and shows a clear difference between extremism and genuine faith. Especially some of the elements of extremist religion that are so closely tied to extreme nationalism. Nationalism is an idolatry that infects religion and turns it poisonous. People think religion is the problem. It isn't. It is extreme nationalism that wears the mask of religion. God is on my country's side.... No. God is on the side of human beings period. Men women and children of all colors, creeds and countries. The Jew and the Gentile... The slave and the free....Would love to a see a game point out those more nuanced realities.

Title: Far Cry 5: Official Announce Trailer | Ubisoft [NA]
Comment: While the idea of the villains being American religious extremists isn't a bad idea, TV shows have used that idea for years so it's nothing new. The idea that they are as threatening as the kind of foes faced in previous far cry games is a bit sketchy, third world warlords, drug cartels, those can create the kind of lawless free for all environment Far Cry games are known for. Assuming the game takes place in the modern era, the U.S. Strikes me as a place that would be a little hard to do, I just don't see the protagonist having to wage a one man war against the villains when their actions (assault, murder, etc.) would become public pretty quickly and would likely end with the army on their doorstep. Waco Texas is a good example of how quickly something like that would not only be dealt with, but contained to a single place and not an entire region, the Jamestown cult on the other hand set up shop on foreign soil so that was not as simple to deal with. Granted this is just a trailer and the game may explain how a region within U.S borders can turn into the village from RE4 without the parasites.

Title: Far Cry 5: Official Announce Trailer | Ubisoft [NA]
Comment:
The game is clearly not trying to offend Christians. It's a massive stereotyping of things like the Branch Davidians and militia/preppers that probably care more about gun control laws than Baby Jesus. Same way Wildlands was a mass stereotyping of cartels. That game had the word "sicario" in its dialog about a million times and would have had it in the dialog zero times if the movie never got made. It drew 99% of its "inspiration" from pop culture like Sicario, Narcos, and Breaking Bad.

I, for one, am at least glad Ubisoft is taking yet another risk. Because Primal was a HUGE risk and paid off. The game wasn't going to win any awards, but it was a pleasant change of pace from the "bigger and better" route that tends to cripple a franchise if they stick with it too long and end up not knowing where to take it. Probably why EA took Battlefield back to WWI, and Activision responded by taking COD back to WWII. And even Assassins Creed seems to be doing the same from what little I've read about the new one.

I just hope the game isn't over-laden with "bible stuff." Because that kinda killed Outlast 2 for me. Seemed like it intentionally perverted peoples' religion as a crutch for the story.

Title: Far Cry 5: Official Announce Trailer | Ubisoft [NA]
Comment: I love the Far Cry series so far. Looking at how the game has been and what its become is certainly crazy but in my opinion I think it keeps improving. It went from this realistic FPS survival shooter to this fast pace action game. I love both these themes in Far Cry and I'm extremely excited to see what Far Cry 5 will have to offer, but I'm absolutely curious on how you will combine what seems like a more urban theme to the game with a survival element which is featured in practically every game in the series. I noticed if you get the special or ultimate edition there are items that come with it. I noticed one of the item packs you can get is called the Doomsday Prepper Pack. When I look at this then I think more of a "Everything is abandoned and society is collapsing" feel. Will the survival aspect of the game be about scavenging the civilized areas of the open world instead of facing the brutal wilderness, or is this name just referring to the setting of  the story where a group of extremists are causing anarchy in this small Montana town because a preacher is spreading information to others on how the world is going to end because everyone is unholy?

Comment:
A lot of people seem to say "It's about time America is the antagonist in a video game" and then hate on people who are pissed about it, when the reason some people are pissed is because they are actually targeting "America" specifically, when in past Far Cry games, it was fictional places that resembled real regions. And to those people who are saying "It's not christians, it's a cult", the actually promotional art was a reference to the last supper. I'm in no way religious. I think the idea of a "God" is silly. But it's clear that video games lately have a liberal agenda to push the idea of antagonistic white America. You're not empowering minorities. You're just flipping the same coin onto it's other side. Same with the growing number of "Strong female leads". It's fine to have them, but when two Star Wars movies and a Star Wars game release with "Strong female leads" consecutively, the agenda becomes apparent. Video games are falling into the same pit that Hollywood fell into. Diversity is great! But when you cry "islamophobia is bad, bring on political correctness" and then cheer when a game is about gunning down right-wing christians, that's when a reality check is in order. Leave politics out of games. That goes for both Left and Right wing.  

P.S. GRAPHICS LOOK DOPE! Can't wait for Co-Op!

Title: Far Cry 5: Official Announce Trailer | Ubisoft [NA]
Comment:
Really need to see that this will be different from most examples of extremist views of capitalism/Christianity that have permeated media over the past two decades. Not opposed to this setting at all, hell i thought if it had more thought put into it, Bioshock Infinite would've had an incredible take on Nationalist Extremism. 

But this looks somewhat generic to me. Like Far Cry took their usual setting of crazy baddies, wild animals, and beautiful backdrops and just applied the american extremism filter to it. What are they going to do to make this experience stand out. What makes this villain different from every other cult leader "prophet"? Ubisoft has the ability to tell good stories when they put effort into it. It's why Far Cry 3 and Vaas still stand up phenomenally well.

But if Far Cry is going to base their games now around "memorable, horrific villains." they have to make this one stand out more. This guy sounds very generic and almost deadpan in his delivery and his design isn't that visually interesting. Not trying to be overly critical or demand they change the game because as a white guy suddenly I'm offended with the portrayal this game brings. 

Just if you're going to bring this particular theme to the table, PLEASE make it interesting, engaging, and/or fun.
